Anonymous Wed 09 May 2018 01:30:38 No.15652572 Report
Quoted By: >>15653109
>>15651512
Her hair is too stiff if it moves in the wind like that. Try grabbing references of long hair in the wind and emulate that feeling of motion because right now that hair is like a single entity glued together to stand up. It’s okay to exaggerate curves to indicate movement. In fact, I’d encourage it, because we often underestimate to what scale we should make limbs and major parts of something bend, and exaggeration/overdoing it can first help you get how parts can move, which can help you adjust it in the future.
A minor fix- I know you’re trying to indicate that one leg is in front of the other, but her left kneecap shouldn’t be that high up relative to her right leg’s because they’re too close to have that big of a difference. Even if there is a large difference, it should be below the right kneecap. If you’re having trouble with perspective, print out a gridded sheet of paper with large boxes and flip it around and shit to experiment with different angles. You’ll notice that lines only start to deviate heavily from the center when they’re near the edge of the paper. Again, exaggerate that feeling when you practice.
